http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Dance Arts Standards of Learning for Virginia Public Schools

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The Fine Arts Standards of Learning in this publication represent a major development in public education in Virginia. Adopted in June 2013 by the Virginia Board of Education, these standards emphasize the importance of instruction in the fine arts—dance arts, music, theatre arts, and visual arts— and, therefore, are an important part of Virginia's efforts to provide challenging educational programs in the public schools. Knowledge and skills that students acquire through fine arts instruction include the abilities to think critically, solve problems resourcefully, make informed judgments, work cooperatively within groups, appreciate different cultures, exercise imagination, and be creative.

http://www.loc.gov/loc.terms/relators/au.value: Board of Education, Commonwealth of Virginia

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Middle School Exploratory Dance Arts

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The standards for Middle School Exploratory Dance Arts introduce students to the study of dance.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Performance, Creation, and Production
The student will demonstrate correct alignment of spine and limbs while performing axial movements, including bending, twisting, swinging, and stretching.
The student will demonstrate correct alignment of spine and limbs while performing basic locomotor sequences, including walking, running, hopping, jumping, leaping, galloping, skipping, and sliding.
The student will develop dance technique skills, including strength, flexibility, coordination, and balance, through replication and repetition.
The student will perform short movement sequences that employ specific space, shape, time, rhythm, energy, and effort requirements.
The student will identify performance practices that promote safe technique and will recognize incorrect performance of physical skills, which can result in injury.
The student will develop personal movement invention, using improvisational skills that include imitation, mirroring, and shadowing.
The student will create and perform short choreographic studies that manipulate the elements of space, shape, time, rhythm, energy, and effort.
The student will collaboratively create and perform short choreographic studies that use unison as a compositional form.
The student will differentiate between constructive and nonconstructive feedback in regard to performance and choreography, using descriptive language and accurate dance vocabulary.
The student will rehearse choreographed dances and execute those dances in performance.
The student will
identify and use safety procedures in all dance settings; and
exercise care with use of theatre facilities, equipment, and costumes.
The student will collaboratively participate in various production-support activities (e.g., publicity, running crew, costume crew, strike and cleanup).
Dance History and Cultural Context
The student will identify similarities and differences in dance styles from various historical periods.

The student will compare and contrast observable elements that characterize the dance arts of various cultures (e.g., line, shape, embellishment, use of color, speed) and create distinctions among them.
The student will identify reasons for dancing, including the use of dance as a form of expression, communication, ceremony, and entertainment.
The student will identify the roles of performers and audiences for various forms of dance.
The student will identify various dance professions.
The student will describe the concept of copyright and relate it to dance.
The student will identify appropriate performer and audience etiquette.
Analysis, Evaluation, and Critique
The student will describe personal work and the work of others in regard to technique, choreography, and performance, using dance arts vocabulary.
The student will describe the similarities and differences in composition and style of dance performances, including live and recorded performances.
The student will identify the role of the dance critic.
Aesthetics
The student will define aesthetics and explain how it is reflected in dance arts and in everyday life.
The student will explain ways in which dance can evoke sensory, emotional, and intellectual responses.
Dance I

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The standards for Dance I provide students with a survey of the dance arts.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Performance, Creation, and Production
The student will demonstrate correct alignment of spine and limbs while standing in a variety of dance shapes and while moving through space.
The student will develop dance technique skills, including strength, flexibility, coordination, balance, and endurance, in response to visual and vocal prompts.
The student will perform extended movement sequences that employ a variety of space, shape, time, rhythm, energy, and effort requirements.

The student will demonstrate fundamental training practices (e.g., warm-up, cool-down, safe stretching techniques, nutrition, hydration) and will identify the relationship between incorrect execution of physical skills and dance injuries.
The student will develop movement invention and improvisation skills, including the use of movement to express emotion, narrative content, and/or the relationship of dance to music.
The student will collaboratively create and perform short choreographic studies that
manipulate the elements of space, shape, time, rhythm, energy, and effort to communicate choreographic intent; and
use a variety of compositional forms, including unison, canon, and ABA.
The student will identify constructive criticism practices used in the delivery of feedback regarding the effectiveness of compositional choices.
The student will demonstrate a range of performance skills, including rhythmic and movement accuracy.
The student will
identify and use safety procedures in all dance settings; and
exercise care with use of theatre facilities, equipment, and costumes.
The student will collaboratively participate in various production-support activities (e.g., publicity, fund-raising, house management, costume crew, lighting crew, running crew, strike and cleanup).
Dance History and Cultural Context
The student will identify periods and styles of dance and artists who contributed to the development of dance as a concert art form prior to 1900.
The student will identify distinguishing features of various dance forms belonging to past and present world cultures, styles, periods, and artists.
The student will explain how dance reflects and records history and culture.
The student will identify various dance-related professions, including those of studio personnel, production personnel, and collaborating artists.
The student will identify systems and methods for recording and documenting dance (e.g., Labanotation, digital recording, written notes).
The student will demonstrate skill in communicating information by researching and reporting on dance organizations and resources in the community and across the commonwealth.
The student will describe the concept of copyright and identify examples of artistic ownership.
The student will demonstrate appropriate behavior as an audience member and as a dancer in class, rehearsal, and performance.
Analysis, Evaluation, and Critique
The student will describe and interpret dance works for technical, choreographic, performance, and production elements, using dance arts vocabulary.
The student will view and compare dance to other art forms and analyze similarities, differences, and the expression of common themes.
The student will read and respond to a variety of dance critiques.
Aesthetics
The student will identify and articulate preferences that form the basis for making personal aesthetic judgments about dance.
The student will describe sensory, emotional, and intellectual responses evoked by choreography and production elements within live and recorded dance performances.
The student will identify aesthetic characteristics within various dance styles.
Dance II

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The standards for Dance II help students integrate and build upon the concepts learned and skills acquired in Dance I.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Performance, Creation, and Production
The student will differentiate between correct and incorrect alignment of spine and limbs while performing complex movement sequences.
The student will develop dance technique skills through kinesthetic awareness and self-evaluation.
The student will perform a variety of complex movement phrases that employ a range of movement elements and stylistic qualities.
The student will identify the impact of physical structure and health and wellness choices on performance and injury prevention.
The student will participate in solo and group improvisations in response to a variety of environments and props.
The student will use improvisational skills to extend the length of set movement phrases.
The student will choreograph solos, duets, or trios that
manipulate the elements of space, shape, time, rhythm, energy, and effort to communicate choreographic intent;
demonstrate the elements of composition, including unity, variety, intent, development, climax, and resolution; and
use a variety of compositional forms, including chance, rondo, and theme-and-variation.
The student will demonstrate the use of constructive criticism practices in the delivery of feedback to peers regarding the effectiveness of compositional choices.
The student will demonstrate a range of performance skills, including dynamics, musicality, movement execution, and the realization of choreographic intent, in performance.
The student will
identify and use safety procedures in all dance settings; and
exercise care with use of theatre facilities, equipment, and costumes.

The student will fulfill the responsibilities of a production-support role (e.g., those of choreographer, costume designer, stage manager, house manager, public relations), identifying the responsibilities and behaviors that lead to effective execution of the role.
Dance History and Cultural Context
The student will identify periods and styles of dance and artists who contributed to the development of dance as a concert art form from 1900 to 1970.
The student will investigate and report on issues of diversity in dance.
The student will research a personally selected career within the dance profession, focusing on the required education and preparation.
The student will examine the impact of contemporary media on the creation and documentation of dance.
The student will demonstrate skills in communicating information by researching and reporting on dance organizations and resources in the nation and across the world.
The student will explain copyright law as it pertains to dance performance, including grand rights for use of music and artistic ownership of choreography.
The student will model proper behavior in all dance-related settings.
Analysis, Evaluation, and Critique
The student will explain criteria that affect dance quality and the realization of choreographic intent, including
development of movement phrases;
elements of composition and compositional form;
technical skill of the performers; and
production elements.
The student will identify and explain ways in which other art forms and technology contribute to dance performance.
The student will describe effective and ineffective artistic choices in composition and performance, using dance arts vocabulary.
The student will write a dance critique, referencing criteria that affect the quality of the performance and using dance arts vocabulary.
Aesthetics
The student will describe how personal experience, culture, and current events shape personal aesthetic preferences.
The student will explain aesthetic responses to live and recorded dance performances, using dance arts vocabulary.
The student will explain ways in which aesthetic responses to works of dance differ from evaluation and critique.
Dance III

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The standards for Dance III help students extend technical and performance skills, apply choreographic concepts, and understand dance as an art form through self-evaluation and reflective-thinking processes.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Performance, Creation, and Production
The student will maintain correct alignment of spine and limbs while performing complex movement sequences.
The student will expand dance technique and movement vocabulary through study of partnering skills, including weight-sharing, counter-balance, and lifting principles.
The student will construct and perform short movement sequences in a variety of dance styles (e.g., ballet, modern dance, jazz).
The student will evaluate and identify personal strengths and weaknesses in relation to the demands of dance technique and performance.
The student will formulate improvisational frameworks in collaboration with peers.
The student will choreograph a small group dance that
demonstrates manipulation and development of movement phrases;
employs a variety of compositional elements; and
uses an identifiable compositional form.
The student will incorporate constructive criticism when creating choreography.
The student will self-evaluate personal dance performance and create goals for improvement.
The student will
identify and use safety procedures in all dance settings; and
exercise care with use of theatre facilities, equipment, and costumes.
The student will fulfill a production-support role (e.g., costume designer, stage manager, house manager, public relations manager) that involves leadership and/or design responsibilities.
Dance History and Cultural Context
The student will identify periods and styles of dance and artists who contributed to the development of dance as a concert art form from 1970 to the present.
The student will investigate and report on the use of dance as social commentary.
The student will research a career that serves the dance profession, such as musician, health professional, dance educator, or dance scholar, focusing on required education and preparation.
The student will create and use a system for documenting personal choreography of short movement sequences.
The student will explain the process for securing permission to use copyrighted music for dance.
The student will participate in audition experiences, demonstrating appropriate audition etiquette and preparation.
Analysis, Evaluation, and Critique
The student will compare the criteria that affect quality in two contrasting dance styles.
The student will identify how personal experience can affect the interpretation and evaluation of dance.
The student will analyze and evaluate artistic choices in composition and performance, using dance arts vocabulary.
Aesthetics
The student will analyze and articulate a personal dance aesthetic and the criteria upon which that aesthetic is based, using dance arts vocabulary.
The student will identify how the aesthetics of a culture influence the dance arts of that culture.
Dance IV

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The standards for Dance IV help students develop independent thinking, personal responsibility, and leadership while continuing to refine dance skills in performance and choreography.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Performance, Creation, and Production
The student will use correct alignment and execution prompts while leading movement sequences.
The student will refine personal movement skills and kinesthetic awareness through exploration of a variety of dance styles (e.g., ballet, modern dance, jazz).
The student will construct and lead movement sequences in a variety of dance styles.
The student will design a personal plan to optimize physical capacity to participate in dance activities throughout life.
The student will create and perform an improvisational work based on a personally selected narrative.
The student will choreograph a solo or small group dance that
demonstrates manipulation and development of movement phrases;
employs a variety of compositional elements; and
uses an identifiable compositional form.
The student will refine personal choreography for performance in response to constructive criticism and defend artistic choices.
The student will self-evaluate personal dance performance and implement strategies for improvement.
The student will
identify and use safety procedures in all dance settings; and
exercise care with use of theatre facilities, equipment, and costumes.
The student will communicate design concepts, scheduling, and technical details with the production team in order to produce a personally choreographed work for performance.
Dance History and Cultural Context
The student will select and research a current dance artist, identifying training and professional background, stylistic hallmarks, and key works of repertoire.
The student will investigate and report on the impact of dance performances as seen in contemporary media (e.g., film, television, social media).
The student will create a plan that outlines specific goals for education and professional development in pursuit of a chosen dance-related career.
The student will create a professional résumé to be included in a personal portfolio.
The student will employ a system of documentation to record and preserve a personally choreographed work.
The student will explain the ethical considerations involved in using copyrighted materials for dance.
Analysis, Evaluation, and Critique
The student will develop and articulate personal criteria for evaluating dance performances.
The student will assess the effectiveness of a dance performance and suggest alternative artistic choices, describing the impact of such changes on the work.
The student will write a critique of a personally choreographed work for inclusion in a personal portfolio.
Aesthetics
The student will write an aesthetic statement to be included in a personal portfolio, citing sources that have contributed to and/or inspired personal perspectives.
The student will investigate and describe how a dance can be viewed from a variety of aesthetic stances (e.g., romanticism, classicism, postmodernism).
